revision.text:
{{Infobox summit | summit_name = Brussels summit | image = NATO expansion.png | caption = Map of NATO members | country = Belgium | dates = November 21, 1985 }}
The '''1985 Brussels summit''' was the 7th [[NATO summit]] bringing the leaders of member nations together at the same time. The formal sessions and informal meetings in [[Brussels]], [[Belgium]] took place on November 21, 1985.<ref name="nato1">{{cite web|title=NATO summit meetings |author=NATO |url=http://www.nato.int/issues/summits/index.html#agendas |work= |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5gWo4KcXm?url=http://www.nato.int/issues/summits/index.html |archivedate=2009-05-04 |deadurl=yes |accessdate=2009-03-18 |df= }}</ref> This event was only the seventh meeting of the NATO heads of state following the ceremonial signing of the [[North Atlantic Treaty]] on April 4, 1949.<ref name="thomas101">Thomas, Ian Q.R. (1997). [https://books.google.com/books?id=mwYQSw00m8EC&pg=PA223&dq=NATO+and+Brussels+summit+1974&lr=&client=firefox-a#PPA101,M1 ''The promise of alliance: NATO and the political imagination,'' p. 101.]</ref>
==Background== In this period, the organization faced unresolved questions concerned whether a new generation of leaders would be as committed to NATO as their predecessors had been.<ref name="thomas101"/> Generational change in the leadership of the Soviet Union brought [[Mikhail Gorbachev]] to the international stage.<ref>Thomas, [https://books.google.com/books?id=mwYQSw00m8EC&pg=PA223&dq=NATO+and+Brussels+summit+1974&lr=&client=firefox-a#PPA130,M1 p. 130.]</ref>
==See also== * [[EU summit]] * [[G8 summit]]
