{{Infobox film | name = 21 Hours at Munich | image = 21 Hours at Munich.jpg | caption = | director = [[William A. Graham (director)|William A. Graham]] | writer = | starring = [[William Holden]] | music = [[Laurence Rosenthal]] | cinematography = [[Jost Vacano]] | editing = Ronald J. Fagan | producer = | distributor = | released = | runtime = | awards = | country = United States | language = English | budget = }} '''''21 Hours at Munich''''' is a 1976 American [[television film]] directed by [[William A. Graham (director)|William A. Graham]] and starring [[William Holden]]. It is based on the book ''The Blood of Israel'' by Serge Groussard<ref>{{cite book|last=Jerry Roberts|title=Encyclopedia of Television Film Directors|publisher=Scarecrow Press, 2009|isbn=0810861380}}</ref> and it deals with real events concerning the [[Munich massacre]] during the [[1972 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Rick Talley|title='21 Hours' relives Munich agony |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/617052192.html?dids=617052192:617052192&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Oct+28%2C+1976&author=&pub=Chicago+Tribune&desc=%2721+Hours%27+relives+Munich+agony&pqatl=google|accessdate=30 July 2012|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=October 28, 1976}}</ref> It was broadcast by [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] November 7, 1976.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bill Carter|title=Munich docu-drama powerful, but why put it on opposite 'GWTW'?|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/baltsun/access/1773290262.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Nov+05%2C+1976&author=&pub=The+Sun+%281837-1985%29&desc=Munich+docu-drama+powerful%2C+but+why+put+it+on+opposite+%27GWTW%27%3F&pqatl=google|accessdate=30 July 2012|newspaper=The Sun|date=November 5, 1976}}</ref> Despite its TV origin, the film was released theatrically in several foreign countries.
==Cast== * [[William Holden]] as Chief of Police Manfred Schreiber * [[Franco Nero]] as [[Luttif Afif]], alias Issa * [[Shirley Knight]] as [[Anneliese Graes]] * [[Anthony Quayle]] as General Zvi Zamir * [[Richard Basehart]] as [[Willy Brandt|Chancellor Willy Brandt]] * [[Noel Willman]] as Bavarian Interior Minister Bruno Merk * [[Georg Marischka]] as Germany's Interior Minister [[Hans-Dietrich Genscher]] * [[Walter Kohut]] as Feldhaus * [[Jan Niklas]] as Schreiber's Aide * [[David Hess]] as Berger * [[Paul L. Smith]] as Gutfreund * [[Hartmut Becker]] as Mattes
