{{About|the 1961 fire|the 2017 fire in Bel Air|Skirball Fire}} {{Infobox wildfire |title= Bel Air Fire |image= |location= [[Bel Air, Los Angeles]], [[California]] |date= November 5–8, 1961 |time= |timezone= PDT |area= {{convert|16,900|acres|km2}} to |cause = [[brush fire]] |buildings = 484 homes |landuse= Residential, wildlands |fatalities= 0 |injuries=112 (est.)<ref name=LAFD1/> |perps= |motive= }} The '''Bel Air Fire''' was a disaster that began as a brush fire on November 5, 1961 in the [[Bel Air, Los Angeles|Bel Air]] community of [[Los Angeles]]. 484 homes were destroyed and {{convert|16,900|acres|km2}} were burned. The fire was fueled by strong [[Santa Ana wind]]s.<ref name=LAFD1>{{cite news|title=Bel Air Fire|url=http://www.lafdmuseum.org/bel-air-fire|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111230004328/http://www.lafdmuseum.org/bel-air-fire|dead-url=yes|archive-date=2011-12-30|first=|last=staff|date=2014|work=[[Los Angeles Fire Department Museum and Memorial|Los Angeles Fire Department Historical Society]]}}</ref>
There were multiple celebrities affected by the fire. Actors [[Burt Lancaster]], [[Joan Fontaine]], and [[Zsa Zsa Gabor]], comedian [[Joe E. Brown]], Nobel laureate chemist [[Willard Libby]] and composer [[Lukas Foss]] lost homes in the fire. Others that fought flames before they evacuated were former Vice President [[Richard Nixon]], actor [[Robert Taylor (actor)|Robert Taylor]], film producer Keith Daniels and singer [[Billy Vaughn]].<ref name=LAT1>{{cite news |title=Bel Air Fire - Framework|url=http://framework.latimes.com/2010/11/07/bel-air-fire/|first1=Scott|last1=Harrison|date= November 7, 2010|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref>
==Aftermath== As a result of the Bel Air Fire, Los Angeles initiated a series of laws and fire safety policies. These included the banning of [[wood shingle]] roofs in new construction and one of the most stringent brush clearance policies in the US.<ref name=LAFD1/>
The [[Los Angeles City Fire Department]] produced a documentary, "Design For Disaster", about the wildfire, narrated by [[William Conrad]].
